    "description": "Right Ventricular Hypertrophy (RVH) is a condition characterized by the thickening of the muscular walls of the right ventricle of the heart. This thickening is often a response to increased pressure within the right ventricle, typically caused by conditions such as pulmonary hypertension, chronic lung disease, or structural heart abnormalities. RVH can lead to heart function impairment, arrhythmias, and an increased risk of heart failure if left untreated.",
    "symptoms": {
      "Fatigue": "Many patients experience general fatigue and reduced exercise tolerance due to impaired heart function.",
      "Shortness of Breath": "Patients may feel increasingly short of breath, especially during physical activities, due to reduced blood flow and oxygen delivery.",
      "Chest Pain": "Some individuals might experience chest pain or discomfort, which can be indicative of underlying cardiac issues.",
      "Palpitations": "A feeling of irregular or rapid heartbeats can occur, often due to arrhythmias associated with RVH.",
      "Swelling in Legs and Feet": "Fluid retention may lead to swelling in the lower extremities due to compromised heart function."
    },
    "treatments": "The treatment of Right Ventricular Hypertrophy primarily revolves around addressing the underlying cause. Management options include: \n1. Medications: Diuretics can help reduce fluid retention, while medications such as beta-blockers or ACE inhibitors may be prescribed to manage blood pressure and reduce workload on the heart. \n2. Lifestyle Modifications: Weight loss, a heart-healthy diet, and regular exercise can help improve overall cardiovascular health. \n3. Treatment of Underlying Conditions: Conditions like pulmonary hypertension should be adequately addressed through targeted therapies. \n4. Surgical Interventions: In some cases, surgery may be necessary to correct structural heart abnormalities contributing to RVH. Regular follow-up with a cardiologist is essential to monitor heart health."
